# ğŸ›°ï¸ tcpdump vs Wireshark â€” Pentester Cheat Sheet

A clean comparison of tcpdump and Wireshark for cybersecurity, pentesting, and networking.

---

## ğŸ”µ tcpdump
**Command-line packet capture tool.**

### What tcpdump does:
- Captures network packets in real time
- Displays packets as text in the terminal
- Saves packet captures to `.pcap` files
- Uses fast, powerful capture filters (BPF)
- Perfect for remote servers and VPN interfaces (tun0)

### When tcpdump is best:
- SSH sessions  
- HackTheBox / TryHackMe VPN traffic  
- Remote Linux servers  
- Lightweight real-time capture  
- Quick debugging  
- Environments where GUI is not available

### Strengths:
- âœ”ï¸ Fast
- âœ”ï¸ Lightweight
- âœ”ï¸ CLI-based
- âœ”ï¸ Ideal for servers & cloud
- âœ”ï¸ Great for capturing traffic to analyze later in Wireshark

### Weaknesses:
- âŒ No GUI
- âŒ Harder to visualize streams
- âŒ Not beginner-friendly for deep analysis

---

## ğŸŸ£ Wireshark
**GUI packet analysis tool.**

### What Wireshark does:
- Captures AND analyzes packets
- GUI with color coding and protocol dissection
- Deep packet inspection (TCP, TLS, DNS, etc.)
- Reassembles streams (HTTP pages, TCP sessions)
- Visual flow diagrams and readable breakdowns

### When Wireshark is best:
- Full packet analysis  
- Malware/traffic research  
- Visualizing connections and sessions  
- Debugging authentication flows  
- Viewing decrypted traffic (with keys)

### Strengths:
- âœ”ï¸ Visual and beginner-friendly  
- âœ”ï¸ Beautiful color-coded packets  
- âœ”ï¸ Deep protocol analysis  
- âœ”ï¸ Easy filtering and breakdown  
- âœ”ï¸ Reconstructs TCP streams

### Weaknesses:
- âŒ Heavy on resources  
- âŒ Not ideal over SSH  
- âŒ Not great for remote servers  
- âŒ Too slow for massive captures

